@p maximum_output_line_length = 200
@i main
@$@<Label@>==@{ASYMP@}
@O@<test2.html@>==@{
@<Head@>@(??@,Asymptotic properties of tests@)


@<Section@>@(Consistency@)
We want our tests to be powerful. For any reasonable test we would expect
that the power will grow with increasing sample size, n. Pwoer being a
probability its maximum possible value is 1. So we would like to have
@<LabDisp@>@((*)@,E(@<phi@>) @<rarrow@> 1 under H@<sub@>@(1@)
as n @<rarrow@> @<inf@>@)
Where is 'n' in E(@<phi@>)? Actually, @<phi@> involves n. Thus, we should
better write @<phi@> as @<phi@>@<sub@>@(n@). In other words, all thes tests we
have considered so far may be thought of as a sequence
{@<phi@>@<sub@>@(n@)}.  
<p>
@<Defn@>@(If @<Ref@>@((*)@) holds then we say that  the test (sequence) 
is <i>consistent</i>.@)
<p>
All the tests considered so far are consistent. The general argument is as
follows. We shall work with only upper one-sided tests (the argument is
similar for lower one-sided or two-sided tests.) 
<p>
All such test have rejection regions of the form
@<Disp@>@(T@<sub@>@(n@) @<Geq@> c@<sub@>@(n@),@)
for some test statistic T@<sub@>@(n@) and some critical value
c@<sub@>@(n@). For all the tests we have considered T@<sub@>@(n@)'s are 
some form of averages, and we have 
@<Disp@>@(T@<sub@>@(n@) @<rarrow@> b(@<theta@>) a.e.,@)
for some function b(.) of unknown parameter @<theta@>. 
<p>
Also, for our tests we have
@<Disp@>@(c@<sub@>@(n@) @<rarrow@> c,@) 
for some c. 
<p>@<Exercise@>@(1@,Show that if 
@<Disp@>@(b(@<theta@>)  &gt; c for all @<theta@> under H@<sub@>@(1@),@)
then the test is consistent.
@)

@<Subsection@>@(Relative efficiency@)
The two properties discussed so far, viz., unbiasedness and consistency,
are sort of sanity checks. A test not meeting these criteria is not worth
considering. Any reasonable test satisfies these. The next question is
given two reasonable tests, how to decide which one is better. 
<p>@<Example@>@(
Suppose we have data X@<sub@>@(1@),...,X@<sub@>@(n@) iid N(@<theta@>,1).
We want to test
@<Disp@>@(H@<sub@>@(0@): @<theta@> = 0 Vs H@<sub@>@(1@): @<theta@>  &gt;
0.@) 
We already have the usual normal test which rejects H@<sub@>@(0@) for
large values of @<xbar@>. Also, we have learned about sign test which
rejects H@<sub@>@(0@) for large values of 
@<Disp@>@(S = @<Sum@> sign(X@<sub@>@(i@)).@)
Both the tests are unbiased and consistent. Which one is better and byhow
much? 
<p>
It is not difficult to guess that the normal test is better, because it
uses more information. Our aim below is to quantify this idea.
@)
<p>

@<Defn@>@(
Let @<xi@> and @<phi@> be two tests based on the same data. Fix a 
@<beta@> in (0,1). Fix @<theta@> in H@<sub@>@(1@). 
Let m be the sample size required by @<phi@> to attain
this power at @<theta@>. Similarly, @<xi@> needs sample size n for the
same. Then the ratio
@<Disp@>@(RE(@<theta@>,@<beta@>) = m/n@)
is called the <i>relative efficiency</i> of @<phi@> w.r.t @<xi@> for power
@<beta@> at @<theta@>. 
@)

<p>@<Exercise@>@(2@,
We could also define a similar quantity as the ratio of the powers
attained for a given sample size:
@<Disp@>@(PowerRatio(@<theta@>,n) = ratio of powers at @<theta@> for
sample size n.@)
Discuss why RE is more applealing than this definition.
@)

The crucial step in computing RE is to be able to compute the sample size
required to achive a given power @<beta@> at a given point @<theta@> in
H@<sub@>@(1@). 
<p>@<Exercise@>@(3@,
Suppose that we have data
@<Disp@>@(X@<sub@>@(1@),...,X@<sub@>@(n@) iid N(@<theta@>,1).@)
We want to test 
@<Disp@>@(H@<sub@>@(0@): @<theta@> = 0 Vs H@<sub@>@(1@): @<theta@>  &gt; 0
@)
at 5% level.
We shall use the usual parametric test. What sample size do you need to
get power @<beta@> = 0.8 if actual @<theta@> = 1?
@)
<p>
Finding required sample size is easy if the distribution of the test
statistic is manageable for the given @<theta@>. For most nonparametric
tests, however, it is difficult. So one needs to use asymptotic
approximations. This is shown below.
<p>@<Exercise@>@(4@,
Again consider the same problem as above. But this time we shall use the sign
test. The exact distribution of the sign test statistic, S,  is Binomial(n,p)
where p = P(X  &gt; 0). Since binomial distribution is difficult to work
with for large n, we shall use the normal approximation:
@<Disp@>@(S ~ AN(np, np(1-p))@)
Compute p for @<theta@>=1. Using the above approximate distribution find
the sample size required to achieve power @<beta@>=0.8 at @<theta@>=1.
@)
<p>
Taking the ratio of the sample sizes obtained in the last two exercises
yields approximate RE(1,0.8) for sign test at level 5% wrt normal test at
the same level. It is
approximate because we have approximated the distribution of S with a
normal 
distribution using CLT.

@<Subsection@>@(Asymptotic relative efficiency (ARE)@)
There is a little mathematical flaw in the way we computed RE for sign test
wrt normal test above. 
To use CLT we need n going to @<inf@>. Now, here n is not a free
parameter. It is just a finite number which is computed from @<beta@> and
@<theta@>. So the problem does not involve any limit whatsoever yet we
have used CLT to get an "aproximation". In the eye of the practising
statistician this is of course a minor point. But in order to keep our
mathematical concsience clear, we define an asymptotic version of RE where
the large sample approximation can be mathematically justified.<p>
The main idea behind the definition that we are about to present is
this. We want to compare two test sequences
 with power @<beta@> at some point
@<theta@> in H@<sub@>@(1@). Also, we want to let sample size, n,
 tend to infinity. 
Since out of the three quantities 
@<Disp@>@(@<beta@>, @<theta@> and n@)
any two determines the other, we cannot keep both @<beta@> and @<theta@>
fixed and yet let n tend to infinity. So we let @<theta@> vary as
follows. 
<p><b>Notation:</b>For a test sequence @<phi@> = {@<phi@>@<sub@>@(n@)} and
a sequence of simple alternatives 
@<theta@>={@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@)}, define 
@<Disp@>@(power(@<phi@>,@<theta@>,n) = 
E(@<phi@>@<sub@>@(n@)) at @<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@).@)
<p>
This notation is not standard. It is only for use in these classnotes.
<p>
@<Defn@>@(
We have a test (sequence) {@<phi@>@<sub@>@(n@)}. 
Fix @<beta@> in (0,1).
Call a sequence 
@<theta@>={@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@)} in H@<sub@>@(1@) <i>contiguous</i> if 
@<Disp@>@(power(@<phi@>,@<theta@>,n) @<rarrow@> @<beta@>@)
as n goes to infinity.
@)
Note that for a given @<phi@> and @<beta@> there may be many contiguous
sequences. 

<p>@<Exercise@>@(5@,
Consider the normal test above at level 5%. Show that
{@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@)}
is contiguous  at @<beta@> = 0.8 iff 
@<Disp@>@(sqrt(n)*@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@) @<rarrow@> 
@<Phiinv@>(0.95)+@<Phiinv@>(0.8)@)
@)

<p>
@<Defn@>@(Let @<phi@> and @<xi@> be two test sequences 
for the same H@<sub@>@(0@) and H@<sub@>@(1@). Fix @<beta@> in
(0,1). Let {@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@)} be one contiguous sequence for
@<phi@>. Let f(n) be the sample size such that
@<Disp@>@(power(@<xi@>,@<theta@>,f(n)) @<rarrow@> @<beta@>.@)
If the limit of
@<Disp@>@(n/f(n)@)
exists as n tends to infinity, and the limit is free of
{@<theta@>@<sub@>@(n@)} then we call this limit as the <i>asymptotic
relative 
efficiency (ARE)</i> of @<xi@> wrt @<phi@> at @<theta@> for power
@<beta@>.
@)
<p>
You should remember that the not-too-rigourous method of
approximating the RE yields essentially the same result as ARE. The latter
is useful only to soothe our mathematical conscience.
<p>@<Exercise@>@(6@,
Use the contiguous sequence from the last exercise
to show that the ARE of the sign test wrt the
normal test (both at level 5%) at @<beta@> = 0.8 is 2/@<pi@> (about 64%).
 In particular, note that this ARE does
not depend on @<beta@>. 
@)

@<Tail@>
@}
